{{Main|United States Treasury security}}
{{for|additional information|wikipedia:United States Treasury security}}

'''Treasury bonds''' and Treasury notes are two types of marketable [[United States Treasury security |United States Treasury securities]]. The Treasury issues both [[Nominal bond|nominal bonds]], the subject of this article, and [[Treasury Inflation Protected Security|inflation-protected bonds]].<ref group="note"> Government agencies also issue debt, some of which is backed by the full faith and credit of the government and some of which is not</ref> Treasury bonds possess the advantages inherent in treasury securities: the bonds are backed by the full faith and credit of the US government;<ref>{{cite web| url=https://treasurydirect.gov/about/| title=About| publisher=TreasuryDirect| accessdate=August 1, 2025}}</ref> treasury bond interest income is exempt from state and local income tax; and treasury bonds currently being issued are not [[Wikipedia:Callable bond | callable]]; although some older issues available on the secondary market are callable.

Nominal Treasury bonds are issued in two maturity ranges:
*Notes have a range between one year and ten years;<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.treasurydirect.gov/marketable-securities/treasury-notes/| title=Treasury Notes| publisher=TreasuryDirect| accessdate=August 1, 2025}}</ref>
*Bonds have a range greater than ten years.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.treasurydirect.gov/marketable-securities/treasury-bonds/| title=Treasury Bonds| publisher=TreasuryDirect| accessdate=August 1, 2025}}</ref>

In this article both notes and bonds are referred to as "bonds". 

==Purchasing bonds==

Treasury bonds can be purchased through brokerages and banks, as well as through an individual or entity account at [https://www.treasurydirect.gov/ TreasuryDirect]. However, TreasuryDirect cannot be used to purchase bonds intended for IRAs.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://treasurydirect.gov/laws-and-regulations/department-circulars/| title=Code of Federal Regulations (CFR) Department Circulars| publisher=TreasuryDirect| accessdate=August 1, 2025}}</ref>

