'''{{PAGENAME}}''' is when investors make regular, equal payments into a [[Mutual fund|mutual fund]], trading account or [[Employer Retirement Plans Overview|retirement account,]] such as a [[401(k)]]. Systematic investing encourages you to establish a regular savings habit, and because you make purchases at various market prices, in essence you [[Dollar cost averaging|dollar-cost-average]] the average purchase price of your investments.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/systematicinvestmentplan.asp| title=Systematic Investment Plan (SIP): Definition and Example| publisher=Investopedia| accessdate=September 17, 2025}}</ref>
The way most investors invest systematically is in employer-provided contributory retirement plans. However, investment firms generally offer programs that let you set up individual systematic investment. These programs include [[#Automatic investment plans|Automatic investment plans]] and [[#Contractual investment plans|Contractual investment plans]].
==Automatic investment plans== Many providers offer an '''Automatic Investment Plan''' (AIP), an investment program that lets you contribute small amounts of money in regular (monthly, quarterly, semiannual, or annual) intervals. Funds are automatically deducted from your checking/savings account or paycheck.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.investopedia.com/terms/a/automaticinvestmentplan.asp| title=Automatic Investment Plan: How it Works, Different Types| publisher=Investopedia| accessdate=September 17, 2025}}</ref> AIPs most commonly offer [[mutual fund]]s (both in [[Principles of Tax-Efficient Fund Placement|taxable accounts]] and [[Traditional IRA|IRA]] accounts), [[Variable Annuity|variable annuity]] subaccounts, and [[529 plans|529 savings plan]] funds.<ref group="note">For an example of AIP, see: {{cite web| url=https://www.fidelity.com/learning-center/personal-finance/automate-savings| title=Automated investing: How to save and invest more| publisher=Fidelity| accessdate=September 17, 2025}}</ref>
If you want to establish an AIP following the [[Bogleheads' philosophy]], consider establishing AIP programs with low cost no-load mutual funds, no-load low cost variable annuities, and direct sold [[529 cost comparisons|low-cost 529 plan]] portfolios.
==Contractual investment plans== {{Warning|In an investor alert regarding contractual plans FINRA offers the following advice:<ref name="FINRA"/> {{blockquote|For a specific type of systematic investment plan—sometimes referred to as a "contractual plan" or "periodic payment plan"—an investor must make a long-term commitment of 10 or 15 years. While the majority of these plans are sold to military personnel, they are also sold to civilians. These plans come with high upfront costs and are expensive if the full term of payment is not completed. If your goal is to save for retirement, most employer savings and retirement plans allow you to save through payroll deduction. Military personnel can make long-term periodic investments in the U.S. Thrift Savings Plan. This plan has no up-front load and low on-going expenses}}}}
Systematic Investment Plans (SIPs) in the US are regulated as Periodic Investment Plans under the federal securities laws. A typical SIP contractual plan lets you accumulate shares of a mutual fund indirectly by making small regular monthly payments, usually as little as $50, over a period of 10, 15 or 25 years. Historically, the majority of contractual plans have been sold to [[Military finances|military personnel]]. These plans impose high upfront commission costs, as much as 50% of the first year payments, and are especially expensive if the full term of the plan is not completed.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/investor_protection_guide_systematic_investment_plan_%28sip%29| title=Investor Protection Guide: Systematic Investment Plan (SIP)| publisher=Legal Information Institute| accessdate=September 17, 2025}}</ref>
Contractual plans have the following characteristics:<ref name="FINRA">{{cite web| url=http://www.finra.org/Investors/ProtectYourself/InvestorAlerts/MutualFunds/p012785A| title=Systematic Investment Plans—Educate Yourself Before You Enlist| publisher=FINRA| url-status=dead| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117214257/http://www.finra.org/investors/alerts/systematic-investment-plans| archive-date=January 17, 2019}}</ref> *'''High first-year cost'''. You are required to pay a creation and sales charge equal to as much as 50 percent of the first 12 monthly investments. If you increase the amount of your monthly payments, you may owe an additional creation and sales charge on the new investment. *'''Long-term investment'''. Typically, systematic investment plans require 180 fixed monthly payments over a 15-year period, with the option of making payments for up to 25 years (300 investments). *'''No direct mutual fund ownership.''' Investments in a contractual plan are placed in a trust. The trust invests your regular payments, minus fees and expenses, in shares of a mutual fund. *'''Missed Payments'''. The sponsor may terminate your plan if you fail to make investments for a period of 6 or 12 consecutive months. *'''Fees and expenses'''. Plan expenses include creation and sales charge fees, mutual fund management and distribution expenses, and various custodial and service fees. The following table shows the cost burden of the creation and sales charge: :{| class="wikitable" align="center" |+ Contractual plan creation and sales fee expense |- ! Contributions discontinued after !! Creation and sales fee as percentage of investment |- | 12 payments || 50% |- | 18 payments || 31.6% |- | 24 payments || 25% |- | 60 payments || 10% |- | 180 payments || 5% |- | 360 payments || 3.3% |} *'''Cancellation and Refund Rights'''. An investor in a contractual plan can cancel the contract with the following rights: **'''45-Day Cancellation Right'''. You will receive a notice of your cancellation rights within 60 days after your first investment in the plan. You can cancel your plan within 45 days of the mailing date of that notice. If you choose to cancel your plan, you will receive a cash refund equal to (1) the current value of your investment and (2) the total sales and creation charge you paid. The current value of your shares may be more or less than your original investment. **'''18-Month Cancellation Right.''' You are also able cancel the plan within 18 months after your first investment in the plan. If you choose to cancel your plan after the 45-day cancellation period, you will receive a cash refund equal to (1) the current value of your investment and (2) the amount of the sales and creation charge you paid that exceeds 15 percent of the total investments you have made in the plan. You should receive a notice of your 18-month cancellation right if you miss (1) three or more of your monthly investment payments during the first 15 months of the plan or (2) one or more payments after the first 15 months. :If you cancel your plan after 18 months, you will not be entitled to a refund of any creation and sales charge. This charge can be up to 50 percent of your periodic investments.
